data.content:
This is a **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in `Span<T>` / `ReadOnlySpan<T>` conversions change overload resolution. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

The `MemoryExtensions.Contains` overload **cannot be represented in an expression tree**, so it throws at runtime when the expression tree interpreter tries to invoke it.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to pick the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 3: Static invocation
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Any of these prevents the span overload from being selected, keeping the call representable in an expression tree.
